#week-title("Three", "Westcott's Triple Point & Canseliet on Ego-Mortality")

=== Core Teaching

Two philosophical frameworks, read together, define the inner demands of Year
Three's mineral work more precisely than any single text alone.

*Westcott's Triple Point — The Science of Alchemy.* William Wynn Westcott
articulates what he calls the triple point of alchemical practice: alchemy
operates simultaneously on three levels, and a practitioner who attends to
only one is not practising the Art in its fullness.

- *The Terrestrial level:* The actual physical work with metals and minerals;
  the transformation of matter through laboratory operations. This is the
  level most practitioners begin with and many never leave.
- *The Human level:* The ethical and religious purification of the practitioner
  — what the tradition has always called the inner work. The practitioner must
  pass through tribulation and anguish, symbolised by the alchemical colour
  stages (Nigredo, Albedo, Citrinitas, Rubedo), before rising to a higher life.
  Westcott notes that the great alchemical texts are fundamentally religious
  documents as much as laboratory manuals.
- *The Cosmic level:* The operation of universal laws — the same laws that
  govern the mineral's development govern the practitioner's and the cosmos's.
  Alchemy at the Cosmic level is the comprehension of these laws and the
  deliberate alignment of all work with them.

The move into mineral work is not merely a change of laboratory subject.
It is a deepening of all three levels simultaneously. The mineral kingdom
demands more of the practitioner's terrestrial precision (the hazards are
real), more of their human purification (the inner work intensifies), and
more of their cosmic comprehension (the timescales and forces involved are
vastly greater than in the vegetable kingdom).

*Canseliet on Ego-Mortality.* Eugène Canseliet, writing from within the
hermetic tradition he received from Fulcanelli, insists on what he calls
the transcendence of identity — the practitioner's doffing of "ego-mortality"
to enter the Absolute. The biographical details of the alchemist are
irrelevant; the Work is what remains. Canseliet is not speaking in metaphors.
He is describing a practical requirement of advanced work: the attachment to
outcomes, timelines, and personal recognition must be genuinely released if
the mineral work is to proceed. This is not the same thing as indifference —
the practitioner must care deeply about the Work. But caring about the Work
and needing to be seen as the one who accomplished it are incompatible at this
level.

For the Adept beginning Year Three, this means releasing the accumulated
identity of "student completing a curriculum" and entering the identity of
"practitioner whose work has no foreseeable end."

=== Topics This Week

- Westcott's triple point: Terrestrial, Human, and Cosmic dimensions of alchemy
- The move to mineral work as a deepening of all three levels simultaneously
- Canseliet on ego-mortality: releasing personal identity in service of the Work
- The difference between caring for the Work and needing credit for it
- Reviewing personal motivations as Year Three begins

#inner-work[
  *The Triple Point Audit*

  Review your alchemical work across all three years through Westcott's three
  lenses:

  *Terrestrial:* Where has your laboratory work been most genuinely careful and
  attentive? Where has it been careless, rushed, or performed?

  *Human:* What tribulations — inner Nigredo passages, periods of genuine doubt
  or darkness — have you moved through? What has been purified? What remains?

  *Cosmic:* What moments in the Work have given you a sense of operating within
  laws larger than your own intention? When has the Work felt like it was doing
  itself through you rather than being done by you?

  Write one paragraph per level. Be honest at the level of Canseliet's standard:
  no ego-flattery.
]

